===Voice===
The voice of Brian is provided by series creator Seth MacFarlane, who also provides the voice for [[Peter_Griffin|Peter Griffin]], [[Stewie_Griffin|Stewie Griffin]], and [[Glenn_Quagmire|Glenn Quagmire]]. In addition, MacFarlane provides the voices for various other recurring and one-time only characters, most prominently those of news anchor Tom Tucker, Lois' father [[List_of_characters_in_Family_Guy|Carter Pewterschmidt]], and [[List_of_characters_in_Family_Guy|Dr. Elmer Hartman]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Cartoonist MacFarlane funny guy of Fox's 'Family' Subversive voice of series is his|work=[[USA_Today|USA Today]]|author=Graham, Jefferson|date=January 29, 1999|page=E7}}</ref> MacFarlane has been part of the main voice cast from the beginning of the series, and has always voiced Brian from the start.<ref name="TVGuide cast">{{cite web|url=http://www.tvguide.com/tvshows/family-guy/cast/100148 |title=Family Guy Cast and Details |work=[[TV_Guide|TV Guide]] |accessdate=August 24, 2009}}</ref> MacFarlane chose to voice Peter and the rest of his characters' voices himself, believing it would be easier to portray the voices he already envisioned than for someone else to attempt it.<ref name="MacFarlaneTIME"/>{{quote box|align=left|width=30em|quote="Part of it was the fact that there was no money, initially. Part of it is that it's just the way I like to work. I like the freedom of being able to just get in there and do it myself. To look at a storyboard and be involved with what the visual acting looks like, as well as the voice acting, is nice. It frees me up to do jokes that are maybe unconventional that need to be done an exact, specific way, that can only be done by involvement with both parts of the process."|source=Seth MacFarlane, on voicing the characters, Interview with ''[[The_Onion|The Onion]]''.<ref name=avclub/>}}

While the voices of Peter and Stewie were inspired from a security guard and [[Rex_Harrison|Rex Harrison]], respectively, Brian's voice is MacFarlane's normal speaking voice. MacFarlane noted in an interview that a reason that he voices Peter and the rest of the characters he portrays is because they had a small budget and because he prefers to have the freedom of doing it himself.<ref name=avclub>{{cite web |url=http://www.avclub.com/content/node/23365 |title=Seth MacFarlane |accessdate=September 26, 2007 |last=Rabin |first=Nathan |date=January 26, 2006 |work=The A.V. Club |publisher=Onion, Inc.}}</ref>

There has been one occasion where MacFarlane did not voice Brian. This was in one short scene of the episode "[[Road_to_the_Multiverse|Road to the Multiverse]]" ([[Family_Guy_(season_8)|season 8]], 2009), where Brian was voiced by Japanese actor Kotaro Watanabe instead of MacFarlane in a scene where everything in the world is Japanese.<ref name="cast">{{cite web |url=http://tv.yahoo.com/episode/217820/castcrew |title= Family Guy – Road to the Multiverse – Cast and Crew |publisher=Yahoo! |accessdate=April 4, 2010}}</ref> MacFarlane noted that actor [[William_H._Macy|William H. Macy]] auditioned for the role of Brian.<ref name=avclub/>

===Early life and education===
Brian was born on a farm in [[Austin,_Texas|Austin]], Texas, on an unspecified date. This was revealed in the episode "[[Road_to_Rhode_Island|Road to Rhode Island]]", where Brian and [[Stewie_Griffin|Stewie]] inadvertently travel to Austin and find Brian's birthplace. On the same trip, Brian learns that his mother, Biscuit, died about a year before his arrival at the farm and had been stuffed by her owners and turned into a table. Out of sympathy, Brian (with the help of Stewie) takes his mother's body and buries it in a nearby park before traveling back to Quahog. Biscuit also appears very briefly in a later episode, "[[Chris_Cross|Chris Cross]]". Brian has a flashback, recalling nostalgic memories of his early life, as Stewie sings "[[You_Needed_Me|You Needed Me]]" to him.

Also in "Road to Rhode Island", a [[Flashback_(narrative)|flashback]] reveals that Brian was taken away from his mother at a very young age. From that point until the chronological beginning of ''Family Guy'' it is unknown what happened to Brian, other than he somehow made it to [[Rhode_Island|Rhode Island]] and was rescued by [[Peter_Griffin|Peter]]. However, in the episode "[[Brian_Goes_Back_to_College|Brian Goes Back to College]]" it is revealed that Brian attended [[Brown_University|Brown University]] for a short time during that period but did not graduate. During that episode, Brian goes back to his former college and attempts to finish the course he began. At the end of the episode, despite failing his final exam, he is at least proud that he didn't cheat his way to graduation.

In a later episode, "[[Farmer_Guy|Farmer Guy]]", Brian does attend an agricultural college to help the family on their new farm. His time there was successful, but by the time he returned, the family had turned the farm into a [[Methamphetamine|meth]] lab.

===Personality===
Brian frequently drinks with [[Peter_Griffin|Peter]] and his neighbors Joe Swanson and [[Glenn_Quagmire|Glenn Quagmire]] at "The Drunken Clam," Quahog's local tavern.<ref>{{cite news|title='Family Guy Live' a fresh channel for laughs|author=McNarma, Chris|work=[[Chicago_Tribune|Chicago Tribune]]|date=September 14, 2007|page=1}}</ref> Brian has dated many (human) women throughout the seasons of the show. He mainly looks for women who share similar interests to him. For instance in the episode "[[Brian_the_Bachelor|Brian the Bachelor]]", Brian participates in [[American_Broadcasting_Company|ABC]]'s ''[[The_Bachelorette|The Bachelorette]]'' and falls in love with the bachelorette, Brooke, because they shared the same interests.<ref>{{cite video | people=Goodman, David|date=2006|title=Family Guy season 4 DVD commentary for the episode "Brian the Bachelor"| medium=DVD|publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref> He also dated an older woman named Rita (in "[[Brian's_Got_a_Brand_New_Bag|Brian's Got a Brand New Bag]]"), and a fellow atheist, named Carolyn (in "[[Love,_Blactually|Love, Blactually]]").

Although there have been a few occasions when he has been drawn to women for purely physical reasons: he dated [[List_of_characters_in_Family_Guy#Other_characters|Jillian Russell]], who, introduced in the episode "[[Whistle_While_Your_Wife_Works|Whistle While Your Wife Works]]", became a recurring character in later episodes.<ref name="jillian">{{cite web|url=http://tv.ign.com/articles/745/745534p1.html|title=Family Guy: "Whistle While Your Wife Works" Review|work=[[IGN|IGN]]|author=Iverson, Dan |date=November 13, 2006|accessdate=October 27, 2009}}</ref> Jillian's character personality was designed to be a stereotypical "dumb blonde", a "[[bulimia|bulimic]] cheerleader," and "not the brightest bauble on the tree."<ref name="Barrymore">{{cite video | people=Barrymore, Drew|date=2006|title=Family Guy season five DVD commentary for the episode "Whistle While Your Wife Works"| medium=DVD|publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref>

Brian has a cultured background; he loves opera and [[jazz|jazz]]; and is [[Human_voice|vocally]] talented. In the episodes "[[Brian_Sings_and_Swings|Brian Sings and Swings]]" and "[[Tales_of_a_Third_Grade_Nothing|Tales of a Third Grade Nothing]]", Brian meets [[Frank_Sinatra,_Jr.|Frank Sinatra, Jr.]] and they both sing together on-stage.<ref>{{cite video | people=Smith, Shannon|date=2005|title=Family Guy season 4 DVD commentary for the episode "Brian Sings and Swings"| medium=DVD|publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref> As well as his vocal ability, he can also play the guitar, (as shown in "[[Meet_the_Quagmires|Meet the Quagmires]]") as well as the piano (shown in "[[Friends_of_Peter_G|Friends of Peter G]])."

He tends to hold [[Modern_liberalism_in_the_United_States|liberal]] political positions, even though [[Lois_Griffin|Lois]] points out in the episode "[[Excellence_in_Broadcasting|Excellence in Broadcasting]]" that he is merely a [[contrarian|contrarian]]. However many of his actions and aims throughout the series reiterate his position as a liberal. For instance, his staunch efforts to get [[Same-sex_marriage|gay marriage]] legalized in Quahog, for his cousin Jasper (in "[[You_May_Now_Kiss_the..._Uh..._Guy_Who_Receives|You May Now Kiss the... Uh... Guy Who Receives]]"); his campaign to legalize [[Cannabis_(drug)|marijuana]] (in "[[420_(Family_Guy)|420]]"); and his desire for stricter gun regulations (mentioned in "[[Brian_&_Stewie|Brian & Stewie]]"). As well as his environmentalist behaviour, for example, the fact that he drives a [[Toyota_Prius|Toyota Prius]], and his opposition to household air-conditioning, shown in [[Hell_Comes_to_Quahog|Hell Comes to Quahog]].

It is also suggested on a number of occasions that Brian may hold repressed [[racism|racist]] views; for instance when he barks uncontrollably at a black record producer in the episode [[Don't_Make_Me_Over_(Family_Guy)|Don't Make Me Over]], and then apologizing profusely, saying "Oh my God, I am so sorry I keep doing that ..... I get that from my father." However, in the episode "[[Peter's_Got_Woods|Peter's Got Woods]]", Brian dates a black woman whom he meets at a PTA meeting. He also has a reasonably good friendship with [[Cleveland_Brown|Cleveland]]. Although on one occasion, when Brian was a taxi driver in [[Deep_Throats|Deep Throats]], he didn't pick Cleveland up when he passed him in his cab.

Despite his overwhelming human qualities, Brian still exhibits some traits associated with real dogs, such as being unable to resist playing [[Fetch_(game)|fetch]], being afraid of [[vacuum_cleaner|vacuum cleaner]]s, taking pleasure in rolling around in trash, getting excited by going for a ride in the car, and occasional [[coprophagia|coprophagia]] (shown in "[[Brian_&_Stewie|Brian & Stewie]]" and mentioned in "[[Brian's_Got_a_Brand_New_Bag|Brian's Got a Brand New Bag]]"). As well as this, he occasionally displays behaviors that are hallmarks of [[dog_communication|dog communication]], such as growling, barking, licking himself, and wagging his tail. He also fears the sound of the toilet flushing, so instead of using it, he defecates on the lawn like normal dogs ("[[Bill_and_Peter's_Bogus_Journey|Bill and Peter's Bogus Journey]]"). In "[[Farmer_Guy|Farmer Guy]]", when the family tells him that they are taking him to "the big farm upstate", Brian panics and briefly takes Stewie hostage at gunpoint, believing the family are planning to have him [[Euthanasia|put down]].

It has also been shown in several episodes that Brian is [[Color_blindness|color blind]] like most dogs. He mentions this in the commentary for "[[Road_to_Rhode_Island|Road to Rhode Island]]" as he mentions that he is one of a handful of dogs that can drive and that on his driver's license, under visual impairments, it says "sees in black & white." Another example of this is in "[[Brian_Writes_a_Bestseller|Brian Writes a Bestseller]]" when he says "I said no grey [[M&Ms|M&Ms]], these are all grey", and in "[[Road_to_the_Multiverse|Road to the Multiverse]]", where Stewie tells him to press the red button to send them home; unable to tell which one, Stewie exasperatedly says "Push the big button!".

===Relationships===
Brian's relationship with the Griffin family is different with each member. Peter and Brian are best friends. In the episode "[[The_Man_with_Two_Brians|The Man with Two Brians]]" (season 7, 2008), Peter states that Brian is the one who helps him get out of the trouble of his shenanigans.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.film.com/tv/family-guy/season-8-2008/episode-5-the-man-with-two-brians/23991392|title=The Main with Two Brians from Family Guy|work=Film.com|accessdate=February 27, 2010}}</ref> In the episode [[Dog_Gone|Dog Gone]], when the family thinks that Brian is dead, Peter says that Brian is his "best friend in the whole world". Peter and Brian can sometimes struggle with their friendship, such as in "[[Peter's_Got_Woods|Peter's Got Woods]]" (season 4, 2005), where Peter replaces Brian with [[James_Woods|James Woods]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fox.com/schedule/showinfo/familyguy/fg_414.htm|title=FOX Fall Schedule|last=|first=|date=|work=FOX|publisher=|accessdate=December 9, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090203010846/http://www.fox.com/schedule/showinfo/familyguy/fg_414.htm|archive-date=2009-02-03|dead-url=yes}}</ref> However, at the end of that episode, Brian and Peter become best friends once again, and Brian is seen sleeping at the end of Peter's bed.

Brian has an [[Unrequited_love|unrequited crush]] on Peter's wife [[Lois_Griffin|Lois]], which is used as a recurring joke in the series. His affections for her are first revealed in the Season 2 episode "[[Brian_in_Love|Brian in Love]]", where they both talk about it and agree to remain friends. In the season 6 episode "[[Play_It_Again,_Brian|Play It Again, Brian]]", Brian tries to kiss her.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/the-debarted-the-accdental-terrorist-play-it-again,12845/l|title=The Debarted" / "The Accdental Terrorist" / "Play It Again, Brian|work=[[The_A.V._Club|The A.V. Club]]|author=Koski, Genevieve|date=March 2, 2008|accessdate=February 26, 2010}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| author = Haque, Ahsan | title = Family Guy: "Brian in Love" Review | publisher = IGN | url = http://tv.ign.com/articles/896/896754p1.html| accessdate=December 2, 2009}}</ref> Lois does see Brian as a great help to her though, mainly due to Peter's frequent incompetence to do basic tasks. In the episode "[[Perfect_Castaway|Perfect Castaway]]", Brian marries Lois after Peter is presumed dead (after being lost at sea). Peter returns, but Lois says that she cannot just divorce Brian after all the support he had given to the family in Peter's absence (getting a job at a [[Hummer|Hummer]] dealer). After a short time, Brian tells Lois to go back to Peter, so the family returns to normal. However, Lois then mentions that she would have had sex with Brian, which causes him to angrily go to the basement.

Brian has acted as a third parent for the Griffin children on several occasions. This is most obvious with Stewie due to their close friendship (see below). Brian has helped [[Meg_Griffin|Meg]] and [[Chris_Griffin|Chris]] on a number of occasions, such as when Brian accompanied Meg to her [[prom|prom]] in the episode "[[Barely_Legal_(Family_Guy)|Barely Legal]]" and defended Meg after she was getting picked on by Connie D'Amico, telling Meg she does not "deserve all the crap (she) gets."<ref>{{cite video | people=Moncrief, Zac|date=2007|title=Family Guy season 5 DVD commentary for the episode "Barely Legal"| medium=DVD|publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref> In [[Seahorse_Seashell_Party|Seahorse Seashell Party]], Meg confronts her family because of their abuse towards her, and Brian compliments Meg for finally defending herself. In the episode "[[Dial_Meg_for_Murder|Dial Meg for Murder]]", Brian calms Meg down by showing he does care about her (using an article he wrote as proof), after she had become an armed thug. Brian also gives Chris advice for growing up from time to time.

In the episode "[[Jerome_Is_the_New_Black|Jerome Is the New Black]]", Brian learns that, despite their apparent friendship seen in episodes up to that point, Quagmire actually hates him. Brian tries to befriend Quagmire and asks why he hates him so much. Quagmire responds with a lengthy (somewhat hypocritical) rant, fastidiously pointing out every singly one of Brian's flaws, calling him, amongst other things, "a sad, alcoholic bore."<ref name=QuagmireRant>{{cite web|title=QUAGMIRE TELLS BRIAN WHY HE DOESN'T LIKE / HATES HIM – RANT – YouTube|url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BdbnssEZ_Xk|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=February 20, 2010}}</ref> The animosity between them is also shown in, "[[Quagmire's_Dad|Quagmire's Dad]]", Quagmire beats Brian up, after Brian had (unknowingly) had sex with Quagmire's [[transgender|transgender]]ed father Ida (née Dan). The feud reaches a high point in "[[Tiegs_for_Two|Tiegs for Two]]", when Brian tries to spite Quagmire by dating his ex-girlfriend [[Cheryl_Tiegs|Cheryl Tiegs]]. Quagmire gets revenge in turn by dating Jillian and, after an argument and trade of insults, both women leave in disgust. Quagmire and Brian apologize to each other and reconcile – until Quagmire purposely hits Brian with his car. Since that point, though, the two characters have simply ignored each other during those occasions when they've been in the same place, but are showing signs in some episodes that they are getting to respect each other. In the episode "[[Forget-Me-Not_(Family_Guy)|Forget-Me-Not]]", Stewie puts both Brian and Quagmire into a simulated dream world where they assume Brian is Quagmire's pet, and it quickly becomes clear that their personalities are incompatible. In "[[Life_of_Brian_(Family_Guy)|Life of Brian]]", Quagmire is busy texting on his cellphone at Brian's funeral while the rest of the attendants are openly grieving.

Brian is also friends with Joe Swanson, the Griffin family's next-door neighbor. This was most obvious in the episode "[[The_Thin_White_Line|The Thin White Line]]", where Brian joined the Quahog police force as a police dog. Brian has an estranged relationship with his (human) son, [[List_of_Family_Guy_characters#Relatives_of_the_Griffin_family|Dylan]]. Brian first encountered him in the episode, "[[The_Former_Life_of_Brian|The Former Life of Brian]]", where Dylan was a rude, uneducated, marijuana smoker. After bonding with his son, Brian managed to turn Dylan's life around, making him into a well-mannered young man. At the end of the episode, Dylan decided to leave Brian to help his mother (like Brian had helped him), and Brian reluctantly agreed to let him do so. Dylan next appeared in the episode, "[[Brian's_a_Bad_Father|Brian's a Bad Father]]", where he became the star of a [[Disney_Channel|Disney Channel]] show. Brian attempted to use Dylan's television connections to further his own writing career, which succeeded until Brian was fired and Dylan saw through his plan. However, at the end of the episode, Brian showed remorse for his selfishness, and they embraced.

Brian struggles with his romantic relationships, and his inability to find a long-term girlfriend is often used as a recurring joke in the series. His longest relationship to date was with [[List_of_Family_Guy_characters|Jillian Russell]], which lasted the length of [[Family_Guy_(season_5)|season 5]], but ended when Brian admitted that he did not want a serious relationship with her. Jillian has appeared in episodes since, usually with other men. None of Brian's other relationships have lasted longer than an episode. Some have ended due to the fault of others, for instance Carolyn (from "[[Love,_Blactually|Love, Blactually]]") when she cheated on him with Cleveland. The others have ended because the women found Brian to be too pretentious.

To date, Brian has only had one relationship which has been with another dog: this was his one-time lover, Seabreeze (Carter Pewterschmidt's prized [[greyhound|greyhound]]), from "[[Screwed_the_Pooch|Screwed the Pooch]]". Brian was having difficulty controlling his canine instincts and he went as far as "violating" Seabreeze during a greyhound race. All of Brian's ex-girlfriends (including Jillian, Carolyn, Ida and Seabreeze) appeared in the episode "[[Valentine's_Day_in_Quahog|Valentine's Day in Quahog]]". Stewie gathered them to try and discover why Brian is so unsuccessful in love. Brian and his exes trade insults, before they are all shown in bed together in the final scene of the episode, having had an [[orgy|orgy]]. In the ''Family Guy'' feature-length [[parody|parodies]] of the ''[[Star_Wars|Star Wars]]'' [[Star_Wars|original trilogy]] – "[[Blue_Harvest_(Family_Guy)|Blue Harvest]]", "[[Something,_Something,_Something,_Dark_Side|Something, Something, Something, Dark Side]]" and "[[It's_a_Trap!|It's a Trap!]]"<ref>{{cite web | title=Family Guy Presents: Blue Harvest| work=Family guyblueharvest.com | url=http://www.familyguyblueharvestdvd.com| accessdate=November 28, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.craveonline.com/entertainment/tv/article/family-guy-something-something-something-dark-side-92835 |title=Family Guy: Something Something Something Dark Side |publisher=Crave Online |author=Firecloud, Johnny |accessdate=December 25, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091221064114/http://www.craveonline.com/entertainment/tv/article/family-guy-something-something-something-dark-side-92835 |archive-date=2009-12-21 |dead-url=yes }}</ref> – Brian appears as [[Chewbacca|Chewbacca]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tvsquad.com/2010/05/24/sundays-with-seth-cleveland-strikes-back/ |title=Sundays With Seth: Cleveland Strikes Back |author=Hughes, Jason |publisher=TV Squad |date=May 24, 2010 |accessdate=May 25, 2010}}</ref> Brian, and most of the central characters on ''Family Guy'', also appeared in the [[Pilot_(The_Cleveland_Show)|pilot episode of]] the show's spin-off ''[[The_Cleveland_Show|The Cleveland Show]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.medialifemagazine.com/artman2/publish/TV_Reviews_21/Cleveland_Show_acquired_lack_of_taste.asp|title=Cleveland Show, acquired lack of taste|author=Conroy, Tom|work=Media Life Magazine|date=October 8, 2009|accessdate=October 19, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091014223117/http://www.medialifemagazine.com/artman2/publish/TV_Reviews_21/Cleveland_Show_acquired_lack_of_taste.asp|archive-date=2009-10-14|dead-url=yes}}</ref>

====Relationship with Stewie====
Brian and Stewie's relationship is a prominent aspect of the ''Family Guy'' series, as it is the basis for numerous sub-plots and several main plots during the series. Their relationship is very love-hate; they often argue, but are also very close friends. Brian is generally the only main character who can understand and interact with Stewie, which highlights the importance of this relationship in the show. In the past, they have gone on various adventures (usually under difficult circumstances). Namely in the "[[Road_to..._(Family_Guy)|Road to...]]" series, which is a parody of the [[Road_to...|''Road to...'' film series]], Brian and Stewie have gone on various trips to different locations, including Europe, [[World_War_II|World War II]]-era England, the Middle East, [[Aspen,_Colorado|Aspen]], Brian's hometown of [[Austin,_Texas|Austin]], a number of different realities across the Multiverse and (most recently) [[Las_Vegas_Valley|Las Vegas]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tuftsdaily.com/relying-on-stereotypes-family-guy-sticks-to-its-formula-cleveland-shows-a-softer-side-1.2001650#4 |title=Relying on stereotypes, 'Family Guy' sticks to its formula, 'Cleveland' shows a softer side |last=Phelps |first=Ben |work=[[Tufts_Daily|Tufts Daily]]|quote=The show kicked off its eighth season with another entry in the now-classic "Road to....." series, which allows for many different sight gags and opportunities for a wide range of humor.|publisher=Tufts University |accessdate=August 6, 2010 |date=October 16, 2009}}</ref><ref name="tvsquadroadto">{{cite web |url=http://www.tvsquad.com/2007/01/29/family-guy-road-to-rupert/ |title=Family Guy: Road to Rupert |publisher=[[America_on_Line|America on Line]]|quote=The FG team went back to familiar territory this week, bringing us another "Road to ....." episode. |work=TV Squad |last=Love |first=Brett |date=January 29, 2007 |accessdate=August 6, 2010}}</ref> These episodes are generally considered to be the best episodes of the series, most notably the first Road to episode, "[[Road_to_Rhode_Island|Road to Rhode Island]]", which remains as one of the highest rated episodes of the series to date.

In the episode "[[Brian_&_Stewie|Brian & Stewie]]", Brian tells Stewie that he has considered suicide because he feels that his life has no purpose. Stewie talks to Brian about this feeling and eventually makes Brian see how important and purposeful his life actually is. Stewie reveals to Brian that he would be lost without him and that Brian is the only person he cares about. He also says that Brian gives his life purpose. He then tells Brian that he loves him as an irreplaceable friend. Brian says that he also loves Stewie, in the same way. Their close friendship has been shown in other episodes also, one being "[[Jerome_Is_the_New_Black|Jerome Is the New Black]]"; after Quagmire's rant leaves Brian in tears, Stewie comforts Brian and says that he likes him, so he doesn't need Quagmire to like him. Also, in "[[Dog_Gone|Dog Gone]]", after Brian sinks into a deep [[Major_depressive_disorder|depression]] after he learns that he is considered inferior because of his species, Stewie takes Brian's collar and plants it on a stray dog, before killing it by torching a liquor store with it inside. The Griffin family then believe that Brian is dead and they are all deeply saddened, as they see how important Brian is to the family. Seeing this reaction, Brian is cheered up and he thanks Stewie. 

Thanks to their critically acclaimed episodes and their complex relationship, they are considered by many critics and fans to be the best characters in the series,<ref>{{cite news |url= http://uk.ign.com/articles/2010/01/12/family-guy-stewie-and-brians-greatest-adventures?page=2 |title=Stewie and Brian's Greatest Adventures |publisher=IGN}}</ref> due both to the way in which their individual characters have developed during the series and how their relationship with one another has developed.

Earlier in the series, before the two became friends, Brian addressed Stewie as "Kid."

===Death and return===
{{Main|Life of Brian (Family Guy)|Christmas Guy}}

Brian's death was the main focus in the [[Family_Guy_(season_12)|season twelve]] episode "[[Life_of_Brian_(Family_Guy)|Life of Brian]]". After Stewie destroys his time machine, Brian and Stewie arrive home with a street hockey net. As he is setting it up, Brian is struck by a reckless driver (joked by [[Seth_Green|Seth Green]], [[Chris_Griffin|Chris]]' voice actor, to be [[Justin_Bieber|Justin Bieber]] in the 2014 Comic-con Panel) in a [[hit_and_run|hit and run]], and later succumbs to his injuries at the veterinary clinic. After a month of mourning the loss of their beloved pet, the family replaces Brian with a new dog, named Vinny, voiced by [[Tony_Sirico|Tony Sirico]].

Vinny appears in place of Brian in the opening credits for "[[Into_Harmony's_Way|Into Harmony's Way]]" and "[[Christmas_Guy|Christmas Guy]]". In the latter episode, Stewie still misses Brian dearly, and spots a past incarnation of himself who has traveled forward in time to Christmas. Stealing the time machine's return pad from his past self, Stewie goes back in time and saves Brian's life, joyously exclaiming "you're alive, my friend", when he sees Brian alive. Brian is extremely grateful for being saved, but Stewie of this timeline finds Brian's affections unnerving, not knowing the reason behind them. The episode ends with the family sitting around their Christmas tree, with everything back to normal. After "Christmas Guy" aired, Seth MacFarlane [[Twitter|tweeted]], "you didn't really think we'd kill off Brian, did you? Jesus, we'd have to be fucking high."<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/family-guy-brian-lives-665836?utm_source=feedburner&utm_medium=feed&utm_campaign=Feed%3A+thr%2Fnews+(The+Hollywood+Reporter+-+Top+Stories) |title=Family Guy: Brian Lives |publisher=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref>

